WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.440
story I'm Anubhuti Mishra and today I'm going to

00:00:08.440 --> 00:00:15.400
be talking about allocating COVID-19 vaccines in West Africa.

00:00:15.400 --> 00:00:20.840
So before I get into that, I just want to spend a few minutes talking about my organization.

00:00:20.840 --> 00:00:25.080
I work with Palladium Group, which is an international development organization.

00:00:25.080 --> 00:00:32.520
We work with a lot of USAID-funded projects in West Africa and Latin America.

00:00:32.520 --> 00:00:39.919
I primarily work on this big USAID-funded project called Data Phi, where we primarily

00:00:39.919 --> 00:00:46.720
work on HIV and COVID-19 programs in Latin America and West Africa.

00:00:46.720 --> 00:00:52.680
So we do a lot of data science in public health that involves something like this, building

00:00:52.680 --> 00:01:01.639
optimization models to building anomaly detection models for data quality assessment, to building

00:01:01.639 --> 00:01:09.040
risk score models to figure out who in the population is at a higher risk for HIV so

00:01:09.040 --> 00:01:14.599
that you can optimize your testing resources.

00:01:14.599 --> 00:01:23.720
So in 2021, we were approached by a couple of West African countries with a very interesting

00:01:23.720 --> 00:01:31.919
problem that there was an influx of millions of vaccines from COVAX, Gavi, World Bank,

00:01:31.919 --> 00:01:39.199
USA, into African countries, but suddenly they found themselves with more than enough

00:01:39.199 --> 00:01:45.940
vaccines to meet their needs, but they found themselves very lacking when it comes to supply

00:01:45.940 --> 00:01:48.440
chain issues.

00:01:48.440 --> 00:01:53.919
Just the infrastructure around sending vaccines across the country, vaccinating millions of

00:01:53.919 --> 00:02:01.519
adults in a period of less than a year or one and a half years was a huge problem.

00:02:01.519 --> 00:02:06.480
And we found with a little bit of research and talking to our country partners, we found

00:02:06.480 --> 00:02:12.559
that a lot of countries ended up wasting vaccines because they were just not able to

00:02:12.559 --> 00:02:16.940
administer those vaccines before their expiration date.

00:02:16.940 --> 00:02:21.360
So this was a very interesting problem, very different from what we were seeing in countries

00:02:21.360 --> 00:02:26.300
like USA or European countries.

00:02:26.300 --> 00:02:29.279
So we thought, okay, this is a great opportunity.

00:02:29.279 --> 00:02:31.199
Let's build an allocation model.

00:02:31.199 --> 00:02:37.479
Let's build an optimization model where we'll take into consideration a lot of factors like

00:02:37.479 --> 00:02:46.919
time to expiration, travel time between distribution centers to vaccine sites, how much staff you

00:02:46.919 --> 00:02:51.199
have available at vaccine sites to hesitancy and everything.

00:02:51.199 --> 00:02:54.800
We had a whole model in place.

00:02:54.800 --> 00:02:58.679
But then we faced reality.

00:02:58.679 --> 00:03:04.839
So this is what the vaccination sites looked like in country.

00:03:04.839 --> 00:03:11.160
This is a picture of a mobile vaccine site from Cote d'Ivoire or Ivory Coast.

00:03:11.160 --> 00:03:16.759
And we found that data was being collected across different platforms.

00:03:16.759 --> 00:03:19.160
Some sites had tablets.

00:03:19.160 --> 00:03:24.440
Some sites had paper-based data entry.

00:03:24.440 --> 00:03:28.839
This is what vaccine storage at site looked like.

00:03:28.839 --> 00:03:33.600
Some of the better-equipped sites had a data entry person with a tablet who was able to

00:03:33.600 --> 00:03:38.320
enter patient-level data into an app.

00:03:38.320 --> 00:03:44.199
So essentially, we found ourselves in an extremely low-quality data environment.

00:03:44.199 --> 00:03:50.639
So none of the pillars that our beautiful optimization models could stand on existed.

00:03:50.639 --> 00:03:56.240
We found that, like I said, data was being collected across different platforms.

00:03:56.240 --> 00:04:02.720
There was a lot of fragmentation across the data collection chain.

00:04:02.720 --> 00:04:08.520
Then we found that the stock data was being collected and managed in an Excel-based tool.

00:04:08.520 --> 00:04:12.800
There were four different types of vaccines.

00:04:12.800 --> 00:04:18.000
There was J&J and Sinopharm and Pfizer and AstraZeneca.

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:22.839
There was no data on healthcare staff available at site level.

00:04:22.839 --> 00:04:31.359
So we suddenly found ourselves in a very challenging environment.

00:04:31.359 --> 00:04:41.720
So this is where we decided that we slightly decided to change the final goal of our work.

00:04:41.720 --> 00:04:46.079
So we were no longer looking at building an exact optimization model that should give

00:04:46.079 --> 00:04:54.160
you the exactly correct data on how to allocate vaccines.

00:04:54.160 --> 00:05:01.920
We figured that currently the Ministry of Health is just haphazardly using whatever

00:05:01.920 --> 00:05:05.200
information they have at hand more often than not.

00:05:05.200 --> 00:05:13.320
It is just based on what is the usage rate at a vaccination site or eligible population.

00:05:13.320 --> 00:05:16.279
They are not looking at any other factors.

00:05:16.279 --> 00:05:21.359
So we decided to use some open-source data, pull in whatever proprietary data we could

00:05:21.359 --> 00:05:30.320
get from the government, and combine all of that to create a vaccine allocation tool.

00:05:30.320 --> 00:05:37.760
So this is a list of all sorts of open-source data that we pulled into our tool.

00:05:37.760 --> 00:05:41.640
We pulled in population data from World Pop.

00:05:41.640 --> 00:05:46.359
There was data on healthcare sites across sub-Saharan Africa.

00:05:46.359 --> 00:05:52.040
Then we were able to use a bunch of R packages to calculate travel time, to calculate catchment

00:05:52.040 --> 00:05:55.720
area for vaccine sites.

00:05:56.399 --> 00:06:00.320
That combined with a lot of country data.

00:06:00.320 --> 00:06:07.160
So even the list of data sets listed here were not available at the start.

00:06:07.160 --> 00:06:15.000
We had to, and we're still working with the country a lot to get these data sets.

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:22.000
They started collecting data on healthcare staff available at the site level after we

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:24.200
requested them to share that data with us.

00:06:24.200 --> 00:06:33.839
We are working with them on how to collect these data sets in a routine and a systematic

00:06:33.839 --> 00:06:35.959
format.

00:06:35.959 --> 00:06:42.839
So then this was our approach to creating this vaccine allocation tool, where we would

00:06:42.839 --> 00:06:48.359
combine a bunch of open-source data with country-specific data and create this tool, which gives you

00:06:48.359 --> 00:06:51.839
some sort of an estimate for how to allocate vaccines.

00:06:51.839 --> 00:06:58.040
We are no longer asking the Ministry of Health to look at this tool as end-all, be-all for

00:06:58.040 --> 00:06:59.440
allocating vaccines.

00:06:59.440 --> 00:07:05.399
They should be looking at their ground realities and comparing with the suggestions from this

00:07:05.399 --> 00:07:12.799
model and then making their decisions on how to allocate the tool.

00:07:12.799 --> 00:07:23.600
So when it came to where to build this tool, we wanted to, and I think all the presenters

00:07:23.600 --> 00:07:29.000
before me have mentioned that when you are working in public sector, you're often working

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:33.160
with extremely low data environment.

00:07:33.160 --> 00:07:37.640
Cost is always an issue, so you're always relying on open-source tools.

00:07:37.640 --> 00:07:46.519
So we wanted to build a low-cost, easy-to-use, interactive, and portable app.

00:07:46.519 --> 00:07:50.519
And then, of course, Shiny is the only thing that came to all our minds.

00:07:50.519 --> 00:07:57.079
So we built a Shiny app, and this is what the landing page looks like.

00:07:57.079 --> 00:08:08.359
It exists in both English and French right now.

00:08:08.359 --> 00:08:15.760
So the app lets you change the input language, so that because most of our country staff

00:08:15.760 --> 00:08:23.920
speaks French, Cote d'Ivoire is a French-dominant country, nobody on the data science teams

00:08:23.920 --> 00:08:30.679
speaks French, so we have an English version for ourselves.

00:08:30.679 --> 00:08:40.280
So this is our Shiny app, and you will see that on some of the other tabs, we still have

00:08:40.280 --> 00:08:42.400
text in both English and French.

00:08:42.400 --> 00:08:44.640
That's for our internal reference.

00:08:44.640 --> 00:08:52.159
This app has still not been rolled out, but okay, yeah.

00:08:52.159 --> 00:09:00.599
So the second tab, called Stock Data, essentially just displays all the stock data that we processed

00:09:00.599 --> 00:09:04.239
from the ministry's Excel-based tool.

00:09:04.239 --> 00:09:10.280
You can look at what types of vaccines are available, their batch number, their expiration

00:09:10.280 --> 00:09:19.599
date, number of doses, number of vials available, and we use this information to build the allocation

00:09:19.599 --> 00:09:26.599
model.

00:09:26.599 --> 00:09:35.599
Then we have the distribution network, which displays the distribution network for Cote

00:09:35.599 --> 00:09:36.599
d'Ivoire.

00:09:36.599 --> 00:09:40.059
In Cote d'Ivoire, the vaccines come to a national distribution center.

00:09:40.059 --> 00:09:45.760
From there, they go to regional distribution center, which from there on, they go to district

00:09:45.760 --> 00:09:49.960
level distribution center, and then from there, they're sent to vaccine sites.

00:09:49.960 --> 00:09:56.359
We've divided these into separate maps because obviously it was very difficult to view everything

00:09:56.359 --> 00:09:58.840
in a single map.

00:09:58.840 --> 00:10:10.159
So on the left-hand side, you can see regional to district level distribution maps, and then

00:10:10.159 --> 00:10:16.919
on the right-hand side, you can see the connection between the national level distribution center

00:10:16.919 --> 00:10:23.400
to regional distribution center.

00:10:23.400 --> 00:10:28.880
Then these are the location of all the vaccination sites across the country.

00:10:28.880 --> 00:10:36.599
So in our input data, we do have the entire distribution network, so which sites are assigned

00:10:36.599 --> 00:10:38.919
to which districts.

00:10:39.039 --> 00:10:46.400
This is a list of all vaccination sites, and users can come in here, and they can select

00:10:46.400 --> 00:10:52.359
or unselect any vaccination sites because we often see that the ministry will roll out

00:10:52.359 --> 00:10:53.359
during...

00:10:53.359 --> 00:11:01.799
They'll have periods of vaccine campaigns where they will roll out 50 to 100 additional

00:11:01.799 --> 00:11:06.840
mobile vaccination sites, so that can be added here, and then when they're done with them,

00:11:06.840 --> 00:11:09.359
they can be removed from the model.

00:11:09.359 --> 00:11:18.039
So you can see users can come in and check or uncheck, and then they can save the list

00:11:18.039 --> 00:11:21.719
of vaccine sites.

00:11:21.719 --> 00:11:26.719
Once that is done, they can go over to the proposed distribution tab.

00:11:26.719 --> 00:11:27.919
This allows you...

00:11:27.919 --> 00:11:34.039
The first user input here we have is number of days because of the complexity of the model,

00:11:34.039 --> 00:11:41.200
we needed to ascertain how many days does the ministry have to allocate these number

00:11:41.200 --> 00:11:42.760
of vaccines.

00:11:42.760 --> 00:11:48.799
So they can decide here that we have these current batches, and based on the expiration

00:11:48.799 --> 00:11:55.400
date, we want to allocate all of these vaccines in the next 20 days or 30 days.

00:11:55.400 --> 00:12:01.119
The default we've used is 30 days based on the ministry's feedback, and they can save

00:12:01.119 --> 00:12:03.880
this information and then run the model.

00:12:04.719 --> 00:12:11.559
So once all of this information is saved, we click this button to run the model, which

00:12:11.559 --> 00:12:16.280
will produce your proposed distribution maps.

00:12:16.280 --> 00:12:26.479
So this takes a few seconds, but this is essentially a linear optimization model with constraints

00:12:26.479 --> 00:12:34.840
around expiration date, time to vaccinate eligible population.

00:12:34.840 --> 00:12:39.919
We'll walk through the list of constraints in a bit.

00:12:39.919 --> 00:12:46.200
So this is the distribution map that is generated by the app.

00:12:46.200 --> 00:12:55.320
You can look at the map, and then if you hover over any of the vaccine sites, it'll show

00:12:55.320 --> 00:13:00.960
you the name, the regional depot and the district depot that site is connected to and

00:13:00.960 --> 00:13:06.179
the number of vaccines of each type allocated to that vaccine site.

00:13:06.179 --> 00:13:12.640
So here we can see that this site has been allocated only Sinopharm, so 722 doses of

00:13:12.640 --> 00:13:16.119
Sinopharm and none of the other ones.

00:13:16.119 --> 00:13:24.000
Then we can see here this site has been allocated 960 doses of Pfizer.

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:31.039
So on and so forth, you can click on any of the site and look at how many doses have

00:13:31.039 --> 00:13:41.559
been allocated to that particular site.

00:13:41.559 --> 00:13:46.520
Then there's a map below where, of course, the above map was a little difficult to read,

00:13:46.520 --> 00:13:54.679
so you can filter this map on whichever district you want to look at.

00:13:54.679 --> 00:14:03.919
And here we've selected Abobo East, and you can zoom in and look at the number of vaccines

00:14:03.919 --> 00:14:14.840
allocated to each of the vaccination site connected to this district distribution center.

00:14:14.840 --> 00:14:18.400
So yeah, this is basically the model.

00:14:18.400 --> 00:14:28.260
Once this is done, users can go over to results tab where they can view all of these results

00:14:28.260 --> 00:14:29.520
in a tabular format.

00:14:29.520 --> 00:14:36.200
They can see how many doses of each type of vaccine has been assigned to each vaccination

00:14:36.200 --> 00:14:37.200
site.

00:14:37.200 --> 00:14:43.000
They can download these results, share it with their team, and make decisions based

00:14:43.000 --> 00:14:44.000
on this.

00:14:44.799 --> 00:14:48.799
Then we just have a tab for model documentation.

00:14:48.799 --> 00:14:58.119
But this is the Shiny app for vaccine allocation tool.

00:14:58.119 --> 00:15:00.719
We still haven't launched it.

00:15:00.719 --> 00:15:07.359
Next month we are going to have a training session with our Ministry of Health and their

00:15:07.359 --> 00:15:11.359
COVID-19 team in-country.

00:15:11.599 --> 00:15:17.960
And once this is done, we will be transitioning it off to the team so that they can update

00:15:17.960 --> 00:15:25.599
and use this tool for making decisions, allocation decisions going forward.

00:15:25.599 --> 00:15:33.200
So like I said, this is essentially a linear optimization problem where our main focus

00:15:33.200 --> 00:15:39.159
was our decision variable was to figure out how many vaccines should be allocated to each

00:15:39.159 --> 00:15:48.599
site and the optimization objective was to minimize wastage and while maximizing the

00:15:48.599 --> 00:15:52.799
number of people vaccinated in the eligible population.

00:15:52.799 --> 00:15:57.559
And we ran into, we started with a smaller list of constraints, but over time we ran

00:15:57.559 --> 00:16:05.320
into, as you work with the data, you figure out some additional constraints.

00:16:05.320 --> 00:16:13.440
So it included that we had to rank prioritized batches based on their time to expiration.

00:16:13.440 --> 00:16:18.679
So not only did we have four different types of vaccines, for each type of vaccine you

00:16:18.679 --> 00:16:20.719
could have multiple batches.

00:16:20.719 --> 00:16:28.359
So we had to make sure that the model starts to allocate the batches that expire first

00:16:28.359 --> 00:16:33.640
before it allocates batches that have more time to expiration.

00:16:33.640 --> 00:16:39.599
Then we, yeah, we had to, there were a lot of constraints around expiration date, making

00:16:39.599 --> 00:16:46.719
sure that it's delivered and administered before its expiration date, that there are

00:16:46.719 --> 00:16:52.080
enough people to administer those vaccines at the site.

00:16:52.080 --> 00:17:00.400
So yeah, this is the, our vaccine allocation tool.

00:17:00.400 --> 00:17:07.239
There was a lot of hesitancy from the ministry initially about using R and Rshiny.

00:17:07.239 --> 00:17:12.599
As a lot of you might know that normally in public healthcare, especially in Africa, countries

00:17:12.599 --> 00:17:15.400
tend to use the HIS2 platform.

00:17:15.400 --> 00:17:22.400
So they were extremely hesitant to, you know, work with a new platform, a separate one for

00:17:22.400 --> 00:17:25.920
their COVID-19 vaccination needs.

00:17:25.920 --> 00:17:31.520
But once they saw, what we did to bring them on board was that before we even got any data

00:17:31.520 --> 00:17:34.520
from the country, we built a mock app.

00:17:34.520 --> 00:17:39.920
We traveled to the country, we had a training requirements gathering workshop, we showed

00:17:39.920 --> 00:17:44.520
them the app, they were able to use it and see how useful it can be for their decision

00:17:44.520 --> 00:17:45.520
making.

00:17:45.520 --> 00:17:48.280
And that was essentially all we needed to get them on board.

00:17:48.280 --> 00:17:54.599
And since then they have been extremely active and instrumental in ensuring that we receive

00:17:54.599 --> 00:17:56.680
all the data that we need.

00:17:56.680 --> 00:18:02.599
We have regular meetings with the Ministry of Health folks and their COVID-19 task force

00:18:02.599 --> 00:18:09.359
to ensure that they are abreast with all the changes that are happening, that we are making

00:18:09.359 --> 00:18:11.479
to the model.

00:18:11.479 --> 00:18:17.880
And we are still figuring out some of the challenges with transitioning this tool over

00:18:17.880 --> 00:18:19.479
to the country team.

00:18:19.479 --> 00:18:24.599
Like I said, you know, this is a new tool for them.

00:18:24.599 --> 00:18:26.760
They don't have our programmers on their team.

00:18:26.760 --> 00:18:34.479
So we are continuing to work with the ministry to figure out those challenges.

00:18:34.479 --> 00:18:43.000
But, yeah, and that's where my talk ends.

00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:49.959
I would like to advertise this a little bit since I got a chance, that I am hiring a senior

00:18:49.959 --> 00:18:51.599
associate in data science.

00:18:51.599 --> 00:18:56.040
Ours is a small but growing team, and we work on very interesting problems.

00:18:56.040 --> 00:19:01.760
We don't have huge data sets, but we do have we do build very interesting models.

00:19:01.760 --> 00:19:06.479
So do get in touch with me if you have any, if you're interested.

00:19:07.000 --> 00:19:08.000
All right.

00:19:08.000 --> 00:19:09.000
Great.

00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:10.000
Thanks a lot.

00:19:10.000 --> 00:19:11.000
Thanks a lot.

00:19:11.000 --> 00:19:12.000
Great.

00:19:12.000 --> 00:19:12.000


